{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a31f7f714401bbcc", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\t                                                Pushing the Frontier of Full-Song Generation:\n2\t                                                 Hierarchical Autoregressive Planning Meets\n3\t                                                         Flow-Matching Rendering\n4\t\n5\t                                                                   (Equal contribution; alphabetical by family name.)\n6\t                                                            Junyu Dai, Xinyue Fan, Weiqin Li, Xiangang Li, Yunjia Li, Bin Ma,\n7\t                                                         Yukun Ma, Chongjia Ni, Yufei Shi, Haoxu Wang, Menglin Wu, Jianwei Yu,\n8\t                                                               Huaicheng Zhang, Han Zhao, Shengkui Zhao, and Haina Zhu\n9\t                                                                                  Alibaba Token Foundry\n10\t                                                                                       Demo Page\n11\t\n12\t\n13\t\n14\t                                                                                      Abstract\n15\tarXiv:2607.20253v1 [cs.SD] 22 Jul 2026\n16\t\n17\t\n18\t\n19\t\n20\t                                                  In this report, we present a unified song generation framework capable of producing\n21\t                                                  high-quality full-length music from lyrics, text descriptions, and musical attributes.\n22\t                                                  The proposed framework supports three tasks: Lyrics-to-Song Generation, which\n23\t                                                  generates complete songs from text descriptions, lyrics, and musical attributes;\n24\t                                                  Instrumental Music Generation, which creates music without vocals; and Cover\n25\t                                                  Song Generation, which reinterprets existing songs with different styles while\n26\t                                                  preserving their melodic content. Architecturally, our system consists of four main\n27\t                                                  components: a semantic-aware tokenizer, hybird-LM, FullDiT, and a two-level\n28\t                                                  melody module. The tokenizer encodes audio into 8-codebook RVQ tokens for\n29\t                                                  efficient discrete music representation. Based on these tokens, hybird-LM performs\n30\t                                                  hierarchical autoregressive audio-token modeling for full-song generation. To\n31\t                                                  improve audio fidelity, FullDiT performs full-song flow matching in a continuous\n32\t                                                  VAE latent space conditioned on codec tokens, lyrics, and text captions. For cover\n33\t                                                  song generation, the melody module extracts and discretizes melody cues from\n34\t                                                  reference audio to guide generation while preserving the original melodic content.\n35\t                                                  Finally, we investigate DPO, GRPO, and OPD as reward-based post-training strate-\n36\t                                                  gies for hybird-LM and apply flow-based GRPO to FullDiT to improve musicality\n37\t                                                  and rendering quality. Experimental results on a multilingual automatic benchmark,\n38\t                                                  complemented by the Artificial Analysis Music with Vocals leaderboard, show\n39\t                                                  that the proposed framework achieves competitive performance in the evaluated\n40\t                                                  settings.\n41\t\n42\t\n43\t                                         1   Introduction\n44\t                                         Music generation has recently emerged as a central challenge in generative modeling, aiming to\n45\t                                         synthesize music that is structurally coherent, acoustically natural, and consistent with desired\n46\t                                         musical attributes [13, 14, 10, 9, 21, 30, 29, 32]. Compared with general audio generation, full-\n47\t                                         song generation is considerably more demanding, as music comprises multiple interacting elements,\n48\t                                         including lyrics, vocal melody, accompaniment, instrumental arrangements, rhythm, and long-range\n49\t                                         structural organization. A practical system should support not only open-ended song generation from\n50\t                                         lyrics and text descriptions, but also instrumental music generation [8, 5, 1] and cover song generation\n51\t                                         [15] with controllable style and melodic characteristics. Despite rapid progress in music generation,\n52\t                                         producing full-length songs with clear vocals, natural accompaniment, and high perceptual quality\n53\t                                         remains difficult.\n54\t                                         One core difficulty of music generation lies in its highly compositional nature. A full song often\n55\t                                         contains multiple instruments, overlapping melodies, and rich temporal variation, making it difficult\n56\t\fFigure 1: Results on the Artificial Analysis Music with Vocals leaderboard. The leaderboard entry\n57\tLucky Dolphin corresponds to the proposed system, which was submitted anonymously for evaluation.\n58\tIt achieves an Elo rating of 1,129 and an official rank range of 2–3. Error bars denote 95% confidence\n59\tintervals.\n60\t\n61\t\n62\tto model music effectively with overly compressed discrete representations. In particular, single-\n63\tcodebook tokenization is often inadequate for representing the diversity and complexity of musical\n64\tcontent, which has led many approaches to model vocals and accompaniment separately [16, 32,\n65\t13, 14, 27]. By comparison, RVQ-based multi-codebook modeling is better suited to capturing\n66\tfine-grained audio details [17, 30]. However, using multiple codebooks also makes prediction harder,\n67\tas higher codebooks are more difficult to predict accurately.\n68\tAt the same time, music generation places a high demand on perceptual quality: beyond correct\n69\tcomposition, the system must produce realistic singing voices, natural accompaniment, and high-\n70\tfidelity audio over full-song duration. Existing chunk-wise decoding approaches [13, 29] for diffusion\n71\tor DiT-based synthesis are effective for local generation, but can limit global consistency and ultimate\n72\taudio quality when applied to long-form music.\n73\tIn addition, cover song generation further requires the model to preserve the main melody of a\n74\treference song in the generated output. Although prior studies and tools [15, 25, 4] have developed\n75\tvarious approaches for vocal melody extraction, balancing the note-level melodic structure that\n76\tdefines the song with the fine-grained pitch variations that characterize natural singing remains an\n77\topen challenge.\n78\t\n79\t\n80\t                                                   2\n81\t\fIn this report, we present a unified framework for controllable full-song generation. The proposed\n82\tframework supports three core tasks: Lyrics-to-Song Generation, Instrumental Music Generation, and\n83\tCover Song Generation. The overall system is built upon four main components: a semantic-aware\n84\ttokenizer, hybird-LM, a two-level melody module, and FullDiT. Given lyrics, text descriptions,\n85\tmusical attributes, and optional reference audio, our system generates complete high-quality songs\n86\twith controllable musical style and vocal characteristics.\n87\tThe proposed framework is designed around the following key ideas:\n88\t\n89\t       • Semantic-aware RVQ tokenization and hierarchical modeling. Our system uses an\n90\t         8-codebook RVQ tokenizer to build a semantic-aware music representation, and hybird-LM\n91\t         to capture both musical structure and fine details.\n92\t       • Full-song high-fidelity acoustic synthesis. FullDiT performs non-causal flow matching in\n93\t         a continuous VAE latent space, conditioned on the complete 8-codebook codec sequence,\n94\t         lyrics, and text caption. This enables full-song acoustic rendering without relying on\n95\t         chunkwise synthesis.\n96\t       • Two-level melody modeling for cover generation. The two-level melody module explicitly\n97\t         represents vocal melody with both coarse-grained and fine-grained tokens, improving melody\n98\t         preservation while retaining detailed pitch variation and singing expressiveness.\n99\t       • Preference alignment in post-training. By combining DPO and GRPO for post-training,\n100\t         our system is further aligned with human preferences to improve musicality, controllability,\n101\t         and overall listening quality.\n102\t\n103\tEmpirically, we evaluate our system on a 500-example multilingual automatic benchmark. It obtains\n104\tthe highest point estimate in most reported automatic evaluation dimensions, while the Artificial\n105\tAnalysis Music with Vocals leaderboard assigns the submitted system an official rank range of 2–3.\n106\tThese results demonstrate competitive performance in the evaluated settings. Dedicated quantitative\n107\tevaluation of instrumental and cover song generation remains future work. Overall, the proposed\n108\tframework supports controllable, melody-aware, and high-fidelity song generation, bridging discrete\n109\tmusic composition and full-length acoustic synthesis within a unified system.\n110\tFigure 1 provides an independent external reference from the Artificial Analysis Music with Vocals\n111\tleaderboard [2, 3]. Our submission occupies the third position by point estimate, with an Elo rating\n112\tof 1,129 from 2,105 evaluation samples and an official rank range of 2–3. The gap to the second-\n113\tranked Mureka V8 is only 12 Elo points. Their reported 95% confidence intervals, [1,116, 1,144]\n114\tand [1,134, 1,150], overlap, and the point-estimate gap is small relative to the reported uncertainty.\n115\tAccordingly, at the resolution of this leaderboard snapshot, the two systems occupy the same leading\n116\tperformance tier. This blind preference-based result complements the controlled automatic evaluation\n117\tand suggests that our system’s full-song vocal generation quality transfers to independent user\n118\tjudgments.\n119\t\n120\t2     Method\n121\t2.1   Overview\n122\t\n123\tAs shown in Figure 2, the proposed framework transforms a natural-language music description,\n124\toptional lyrics, and optional reference audio into a complete song. The system first constructs\n125\ta structured textual condition from musical attributes and, when available, lyrics with section\n126\ttags. Discrete audio tokens are then autoregressively predicted by hybird-LM. For cover song\n127\tgeneration, the melody module extracts and discretizes note-level and frame-level pitch cues from the\n128\treference audio and supplies them as additional conditions to hybird-LM. Finally, FullDiT generates\n129\ta continuous full-song VAE latent conditioned on the codec sequence, text caption, and lyrics when\n130\tavailable, which is decoded into a high-fidelity waveform.\n131\t\n132\t       • Semantic-aware RVQ tokenizer maps raw music audio into discrete token sequences using\n133\t         an 8-codebook residual vector quantization (RVQ) scheme. It is trained with a three-stage\n134\t         recipe consisting of BEST-RQ-style pretraining, multi-task finetuning, and discrete token\n135\t         training, ensuring that the resulting token stream preserves rich semantic information while\n136\t         maintaining high reconstruction fidelity.\n137\t\n138\t\n139\t                                                  3\n140\t\f             Lyrics Token        VAE Latent                     Waveform\n141\t\n142\t              Caption Token      BOS Token\n143\t\n144\t                       RVQ Audio Token               VAE           VAE             VAE\n145\t\n146\t                       Melody Token\n147\t\n148\t\n149\t                                                 FullDiT\n150\t\n151\t\n152\t\n153\t\n154\t           Lyrics   Caption\n155\t\n156\t\n157\t                                              Hybird-LM\n158\t\n159\t\n160\t\n161\t\n162\t           Lyrics   Caption\n163\t\n164\t                              Melody-Extractor\n165\t\n166\t\n167\t\n168\t\n169\tFigure 2: Overview of the proposed framework. Given a text caption, optional lyrics, and optional\n170\treference audio, hybird-LM autoregressively generates audio tokens. For cover song generation, the\n171\tmelody module extracts and discretizes melody cues from the reference audio as additional conditions\n172\tfor hybird-LM. FullDiT then generates a continuous full-song VAE latent conditioned on the codec\n173\tsequence, text caption, and lyrics when available, which is decoded into a high-fidelity waveform.\n174\t\n175\t\n176\t       • hybird-LM generates audio tokens conditioned on lyrics, text descriptions, and musical\n177\t         attributes. It consists of an 8B-parameter global LLM and a 0.4B local LLM, which autore-\n178\t         gressively predict the first-level audio tokens and the residual audio tokens, respectively.\n179\t         This design supports both vocal music and instrumental music generation.\n180\t       • Two-level melody module extracts note-level and frame-level pitch cues from reference\n181\t         audio and discretizes them into coarse-grained and fine-grained melody tokens. These\n182\t         explicit melody conditions guide the overall vocal melody and local pitch details, helping\n183\t         preserve the core melody in cover song generation.\n184\t       • FullDiT is an 8B-parameter DiT model that performs full-song flow matching in a continu-\n185\t         ous VAE latent space with non-causal self-attention. Conditioned on the codec sequence,\n186\t         text caption, and lyrics when available, it enriches acoustic detail and overall perceptual\n187\t         quality for high-fidelity full-song synthesis.\n188\t\n189\tIn the following sections, we first introduce the semantic-aware RVQ tokenizer and the discrete\n190\tmusic representation it provides. We then describe hybird-LM for autoregressive token generation,\n191\tfollowed by FullDiT for high-fidelity song synthesis. Next, we present the two-level melody module\n192\tfor melody-guided cover song generation. Finally, we describe DPO, GRPO, and OPD as reward-\n193\tbased post-training strategies that incorporate automatically constructed preference signals, on-policy\n194\trewards, and teacher guidance to improve musicality.\n195\t\n196\t\n197\t                                                   4\n198\t\f2.2     Semantic-Aware RVQ Tokenizer\n199\t\n200\t\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "8c56a85d-92a8-4274-a82c-ece638c779b4", "uuid": "65a190cc-c32e-429a-81dd-4a63ed15cb61", "timestamp": "2026-07-23T07:53:25.375Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_2607_20253.txt", "content": "                                                Pushing the Frontier of Full-Song Generation:\n                                                 Hierarchical Autoregressive Planning Meets\n                                                         Flow-Matching Rendering\n\n                                                                   (Equal contribution; alphabetical by family name.)\n                                                            Junyu Dai, Xinyue Fan, Weiqin Li, Xiangang Li, Yunjia Li, Bin Ma,\n                                                         Yukun Ma, Chongjia Ni, Yufei Shi, Haoxu Wang, Menglin Wu, Jianwei Yu,\n                                                               Huaicheng Zhang, Han Zhao, Shengkui Zhao, and Haina Zhu\n                                                                                  Alibaba Token Foundry\n                                                                                       Demo Page\n\n\n\n                                                                                      Abstract\narXiv:2607.20253v1 [cs.SD] 22 Jul 2026\n\n\n\n\n                                                  In this report, we present a unified song generation framework capable of producing\n                                                  high-quality full-length music from lyrics, text descriptions, and musical attributes.\n                                                  The proposed framework supports three tasks: Lyrics-to-Song Generation, which\n                                                  generates complete songs from text descriptions, lyrics, and musical attributes;\n                                                  Instrumental Music Generation, which creates music without vocals; and Cover\n                                                  Song Generation, which reinterprets existing songs with different styles while\n                                                  preserving their melodic content. Architecturally, our system consists of four main\n                                                  components: a semantic-aware tokenizer, hybird-LM, FullDiT, and a two-level\n                                                  melody module. The tokenizer encodes audio into 8-codebook RVQ tokens for\n                                                  efficient discrete music representation. Based on these tokens, hybird-LM performs\n                                                  hierarchical autoregressive audio-token modeling for full-song generation. To\n                                                  improve audio fidelity, FullDiT performs full-song flow matching in a continuous\n                                                  VAE latent space conditioned on codec tokens, lyrics, and text captions. For cover\n                                                  song generation, the melody module extracts and discretizes melody cues from\n                                                  reference audio to guide generation while preserving the original melodic content.\n                                                  Finally, we investigate DPO, GRPO, and OPD as reward-based post-training strate-\n                                                  gies for hybird-LM and apply flow-based GRPO to FullDiT to improve musicality\n                                                  and rendering quality. Experimental results on a multilingual automatic benchmark,\n                                                  complemented by the Artificial Analysis Music with Vocals leaderboard, show\n                                                  that the proposed framework achieves competitive performance in the evaluated\n                                                  settings.\n\n\n                                         1   Introduction\n                                         Music generation has recently emerged as a central challenge in generative modeling, aiming to\n                                         synthesize music that is structurally coherent, acoustically natural, and consistent with desired\n                                         musical attributes [13, 14, 10, 9, 21, 30, 29, 32]. Compared with general audio generation, full-\n                                         song generation is considerably more demanding, as music comprises multiple interacting elements,\n                                         including lyrics, vocal melody, accompaniment, instrumental arrangements, rhythm, and long-range\n                                         structural organization. A practical system should support not only open-ended song generation from\n                                         lyrics and text descriptions, but also instrumental music generation [8, 5, 1] and cover song generation\n                                         [15] with controllable style and melodic characteristics. Despite rapid progress in music generation,\n                                         producing full-length songs with clear vocals, natural accompaniment, and high perceptual quality\n                                         remains difficult.\n                                         One core difficulty of music generation lies in its highly compositional nature. A full song often\n                                         contains multiple instruments, overlapping melodies, and rich temporal variation, making it difficult\n\fFigure 1: Results on the Artificial Analysis Music with Vocals leaderboard. The leaderboard entry\nLucky Dolphin corresponds to the proposed system, which was submitted anonymously for evaluation.\nIt achieves an Elo rating of 1,129 and an official rank range of 2–3. Error bars denote 95% confidence\nintervals.\n\n\nto model music effectively with overly compressed discrete representations. In particular, single-\ncodebook tokenization is often inadequate for representing the diversity and complexity of musical\ncontent, which has led many approaches to model vocals and accompaniment separately [16, 32,\n13, 14, 27]. By comparison, RVQ-based multi-codebook modeling is better suited to capturing\nfine-grained audio details [17, 30]. However, using multiple codebooks also makes prediction harder,\nas higher codebooks are more difficult to predict accurately.\nAt the same time, music generation places a high demand on perceptual quality: beyond correct\ncomposition, the system must produce realistic singing voices, natural accompaniment, and high-\nfidelity audio over full-song duration. Existing chunk-wise decoding approaches [13, 29] for diffusion\nor DiT-based synthesis are effective for local generation, but can limit global consistency and ultimate\naudio quality when applied to long-form music.\nIn addition, cover song generation further requires the model to preserve the main melody of a\nreference song in the generated output. Although prior studies and tools [15, 25, 4] have developed\nvarious approaches for vocal melody extraction, balancing the note-level melodic structure that\ndefines the song with the fine-grained pitch variations that characterize natural singing remains an\nopen challenge.\n\n\n                                                   2\n\fIn this report, we present a unified framework for controllable full-song generation. The proposed\nframework supports three core tasks: Lyrics-to-Song Generation, Instrumental Music Generation, and\nCover Song Generation. The overall system is built upon four main components: a semantic-aware\ntokenizer, hybird-LM, a two-level melody module, and FullDiT. Given lyrics, text descriptions,\nmusical attributes, and optional reference audio, our system generates complete high-quality songs\nwith controllable musical style and vocal characteristics.\nThe proposed framework is designed around the following key ideas:\n\n       • Semantic-aware RVQ tokenization and hierarchical modeling. Our system uses an\n         8-codebook RVQ tokenizer to build a semantic-aware music representation, and hybird-LM\n         to capture both musical structure and fine details.\n       • Full-song high-fidelity acoustic synthesis. FullDiT performs non-causal flow matching in\n         a continuous VAE latent space, conditioned on the complete 8-codebook codec sequence,\n         lyrics, and text caption. This enables full-song acoustic rendering without relying on\n         chunkwise synthesis.\n       • Two-level melody modeling for cover generation. The two-level melody module explicitly\n         represents vocal melody with both coarse-grained and fine-grained tokens, improving melody\n         preservation while retaining detailed pitch variation and singing expressiveness.\n       • Preference alignment in post-training. By combining DPO and GRPO for post-training,\n         our system is further aligned with human preferences to improve musicality, controllability,\n         and overall listening quality.\n\nEmpirically, we evaluate our system on a 500-example multilingual automatic benchmark. It obtains\nthe highest point estimate in most reported automatic evaluation dimensions, while the Artificial\nAnalysis Music with Vocals leaderboard assigns the submitted system an official rank range of 2–3.\nThese results demonstrate competitive performance in the evaluated settings. Dedicated quantitative\nevaluation of instrumental and cover song generation remains future work. Overall, the proposed\nframework supports controllable, melody-aware, and high-fidelity song generation, bridging discrete\nmusic composition and full-length acoustic synthesis within a unified system.\nFigure 1 provides an independent external reference from the Artificial Analysis Music with Vocals\nleaderboard [2, 3]. Our submission occupies the third position by point estimate, with an Elo rating\nof 1,129 from 2,105 evaluation samples and an official rank range of 2–3. The gap to the second-\nranked Mureka V8 is only 12 Elo points. Their reported 95% confidence intervals, [1,116, 1,144]\nand [1,134, 1,150], overlap, and the point-estimate gap is small relative to the reported uncertainty.\nAccordingly, at the resolution of this leaderboard snapshot, the two systems occupy the same leading\nperformance tier. This blind preference-based result complements the controlled automatic evaluation\nand suggests that our system’s full-song vocal generation quality transfers to independent user\njudgments.\n\n2     Method\n2.1   Overview\n\nAs shown in Figure 2, the proposed framework transforms a natural-language music description,\noptional lyrics, and optional reference audio into a complete song. The system first constructs\na structured textual condition from musical attributes and, when available, lyrics with section\ntags. Discrete audio tokens are then autoregressively predicted by hybird-LM. For cover song\ngeneration, the melody module extracts and discretizes note-level and frame-level pitch cues from the\nreference audio and supplies them as additional conditions to hybird-LM. Finally, FullDiT generates\na continuous full-song VAE latent conditioned on the codec sequence, text caption, and lyrics when\navailable, which is decoded into a high-fidelity waveform.\n\n       • Semantic-aware RVQ tokenizer maps raw music audio into discrete token sequences using\n         an 8-codebook residual vector quantization (RVQ) scheme. It is trained with a three-stage\n         recipe consisting of BEST-RQ-style pretraining, multi-task finetuning, and discrete token\n         training, ensuring that the resulting token stream preserves rich semantic information while\n         maintaining high reconstruction fidelity.\n\n\n                                                  3\n\f             Lyrics Token        VAE Latent                     Waveform\n\n              Caption Token      BOS Token\n\n                       RVQ Audio Token               VAE           VAE             VAE\n\n                       Melody Token\n\n\n                                                 FullDiT\n\n\n\n\n           Lyrics   Caption\n\n\n                                              Hybird-LM\n\n\n\n\n           Lyrics   Caption\n\n                              Melody-Extractor\n\n\n\n\nFigure 2: Overview of the proposed framework. Given a text caption, optional lyrics, and optional\nreference audio, hybird-LM autoregressively generates audio tokens. For cover song generation, the\nmelody module extracts and discretizes melody cues from the reference audio as additional conditions\nfor hybird-LM. FullDiT then generates a continuous full-song VAE latent conditioned on the codec\nsequence, text caption, and lyrics when available, which is decoded into a high-fidelity waveform.\n\n\n       • hybird-LM generates audio tokens conditioned on lyrics, text descriptions, and musical\n         attributes. It consists of an 8B-parameter global LLM and a 0.4B local LLM, which autore-\n         gressively predict the first-level audio tokens and the residual audio tokens, respectively.\n         This design supports both vocal music and instrumental music generation.\n       • Two-level melody module extracts note-level and frame-level pitch cues from reference\n         audio and discretizes them into coarse-grained and fine-grained melody tokens. These\n         explicit melody conditions guide the overall vocal melody and local pitch details, helping\n         preserve the core melody in cover song generation.\n       • FullDiT is an 8B-parameter DiT model that performs full-song flow matching in a continu-\n         ous VAE latent space with non-causal self-attention. Conditioned on the codec sequence,\n         text caption, and lyrics when available, it enriches acoustic detail and overall perceptual\n         quality for high-fidelity full-song synthesis.\n\nIn the following sections, we first introduce the semantic-aware RVQ tokenizer and the discrete\nmusic representation it provides. We then describe hybird-LM for autoregressive token generation,\nfollowed by FullDiT for high-fidelity song synthesis. Next, we present the two-level melody module\nfor melody-guided cover song generation. Finally, we describe DPO, GRPO, and OPD as reward-\nbased post-training strategies that incorporate automatically constructed preference signals, on-policy\nrewards, and teacher guidance to improve musicality.\n\n\n                                                   4\n\f2.2     Semantic-Aware RVQ Tokenizer\n\n", "numLines": 200, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 965}}}
