{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-aa65402d3f6118f9", "type": "tool_result", "content": "200\t\n201\t\n202\t\n203\tFigure 3: Three-stage training of the proposed tokenizer, which consists of BEST-RQ-style pretraining,\n204\tmulti-task finetuning, and RVQ token training.\n205\t\n206\tThe proposed tokenizer maps raw music audio into discrete token sequences for downstream language\n207\tmodeling and acoustic generation. As shown in Figure 3, we train it with a three-stage pipeline\n208\tconsisting of BEST-RQ-style pretraining[7], multi-task finetuning, and RVQ token training.\n209\t\n210\tArchitecture. The tokenizer is built on a 24-layer Conformer encoder, followed by an 8-codebook\n211\tresidual vector quantization (RVQ) module. Each codebook has a size of 8192. Given input music\n212\taudio features, the encoder produces continuous latent representations, which are then quantized into\n213\tdiscrete token sequences by the RVQ module. The resulting tokens provide a compact yet expressive\n214\trepresentation of musical content and serve as the target space for hybird-LM.\n215\t\n216\tStage 1: BEST-RQ-style pretraining. In the first stage, we pretrain the 24-layer Conformer\n217\tencoder with a BEST-RQ-style objective[7]. Masked audio features are encoded and trained to\n218\tpredict random-projection-quantized targets, enabling the encoder to learn robust contextual and\n219\tsemantic representations from large-scale music audio.\n220\t\n221\tStage 2: Multi-task finetuning. In the second stage, we finetune the encoder with multiple training\n222\tobjectives, including ASR, reconstruction, and chroma prediction, as shown in Figure 3. This stage\n223\timproves the representation quality for lyrics, acoustic details, and pitch-related musical structure.\n224\t\n225\tStage 3: RVQ token training. In the final stage, we introduce the RVQ module and train the\n226\ttokenizer to generate discrete tokens. Specifically, we use the bottom 12 layers of the Conformer\n227\tencoder as a frozen feature extractor, while the top 12 layers together with the 8-codebook RVQ\n228\tmodule are optimized for tokenization. This stage yields discrete tokens that preserve semantic\n229\tinformation while maintaining high reconstruction fidelity.\n230\t\n231\t2.3     hybird-LM\n232\t\n233\t2.3.1    Data and Training Pipeline\n234\tThe training of hybird-LM follows a multi-stage pipeline consisting of large-scale pre-training, style-\n235\tbalanced mid-training, and high-quality supervised fine-tuning. We first collect a large-scale song\n236\tcorpus from diverse digital music sources, covering a wide range of languages, musical styles, vocal\n237\tcharacteristics, and production practices. To construct a reliable training corpus, we apply a multi-\n238\tstage curation process that considers metadata completeness together with complementary perceptual\n239\tand musical-quality estimates from SongEval [31], Audiobox Aesthetics [22], and SongBench [26].\n240\tAfter filtering and deduplication, a corpus containing tens of millions of songs is retained for large-\n241\tscale training.\n242\t\n243\tFine-grained music annotation. An overview of the complete data curation and staged training\n244\tpipeline is shown in Figure 4. To provide expressive and controllable conditioning signals, we\n245\t\n246\t\n247\t                                                  5\n248\t\f            Figure 4: Overview of the music data curation and staged training pipeline.\n249\t\n250\t\n251\tdesign a fine-grained annotation system that describes each song from multiple complementary\n252\tperspectives. The annotation taxonomy covers musical style and substyle, mood, instrumentation,\n253\tvocal characteristics, segment-level song structure, usage scenario, and common musical attributes\n254\tsuch as tempo, key, rhythmic characteristics, energy, and production-related descriptors. Structural\n255\tannotations identify segments such as intro, verse, pre-chorus, chorus, bridge, instrumental break,\n256\tand outro whenever applicable. These annotations are normalized into a structured representation\n257\tand, together with lyrics and section markers, form the textual condition supplied to hybird-LM.\n258\t\n259\tStage 1: Large-scale pre-training. The full curated corpus is used to establish broad multilingual\n260\tand multi-style coverage. During this stage, the model learns general text-to-music correspondence,\n261\tframe-level audio-token prediction, and long-range musical dependencies. We pre-train hybird-LM\n262\tusing a relatively high learning rate for a limited number of passes over the large-scale corpus.\n263\t\n264\tStage 2: Style-balanced mid-training. Large-scale music corpora naturally exhibit a long-tailed\n265\tdistribution in which a small number of popular styles dominate the training data. We therefore use\n266\tthe SongBench Musicality score to select a higher-quality subset and rebalance it across a broad set of\n267\tmusical style categories, including Pop, Rock, Folk, Hip-Hop, R&B, Soul, and EDM, etc. Together\n268\twith additional high-quality instrumental music, this process yields a multi-million-song training\n269\tcorpus. We continue training on this corpus using a reduced learning rate. This stage improves both\n270\tmusical quality and style coverage while reducing over-specialization toward dominant genres.\n271\t\n272\tStage 3: Supervised fine-tuning. For the final stage, we select a compact subset of high-quality\n273\tsongs from the curated data pool. The selected examples exhibit strong musicality, reliable annota-\n274\ttions, clear structural organization, and close agreement between the audio and its textual conditions.\n275\tWe perform supervised fine-tuning using a substantially lower learning rate. This final refinement\n276\tstage further improves musical coherence, condition following, generation stability, and overall\n277\tperceptual quality.\n278\t\n279\t2.3.2   Hierarchical Autoregressive Architecture\n280\tAs illustrated in Figure 5, hybird-LM adopts a hierarchical autoregressive architecture that separates\n281\tlong-range temporal modeling from within-frame acoustic modeling. Following the factorization\n282\tintroduced by HeartMuLa [30], the architecture consists of an 8B-parameter global LLM operating\n283\talong the temporal axis and a lightweight 0.4B-parameter local LLM operating along the RVQ\n284\tcodebook axis.\n285\t\n286\t\n287\t                                                  6\n288\t\fFigure 5: Overview of the hierarchical autoregressive architecture of hybird-LM. Structured music\n289\tannotations and lyrics are provided as textual conditions, with optional frame-aligned melody tokens\n290\tused for cover generation. The 8B global LLM predicts the first codebook token c0t once per audio\n291\tframe and models long-range temporal dependencies, while the 0.4B local LLM autoregressively\n292\tpredicts the residual codebook tokens c1t –c7t within the frame.\n293\t\n294\t\n295\tThe model receives structured music annotations and lyrics as textual conditions and predicts discrete\n296\taudio tokens generated by the proposed tokenizer. Let X denote the textual condition, comprising\n297\tthe structured music description and lyrics, and let M = (M MIDI , M F0 ) denote the optional frame-\n298\taligned melody condition used for cover generation. For non-cover generation, M = ∅. Given\n299\tan audio-token sequence A = (c1 , . . . , cT ), each audio frame is represented by eight RVQ tokens,\n300\tct = (c0t , . . . , c7t ). The first codebook c0t provides a compact frame-level representation for global\n301\ttemporal modeling, while c1t –c7t progressively encode residual acoustic information. Each codebook\n302\tcontains 8,192 entries together with an end-of-sequence token, and the tokenizer operates at a frame\n303\trate of 25 Hz.\n304\tWe factorize the conditional audio-token distribution as\n305\t                                T\n306\t                                   \"                         7\n307\t                                                                                    #\n308\t                               Y                            \u0001Y         g <k\n309\t                                        0                         k\n310\t                                                                                  \u0001\n311\t               p(A | X, M ) =        p ct | c<t , X, M ; θg    p ct | ht , ct ; θl ,                  (1)\n312\t                                 t=1                          k=1\n313\t\n314\twhere hgt denotes the global hidden state conditioned on X and M , c<t represents all preceding audio\n315\tframes, and c<k\n316\t              t  denotes the codebooks already generated within the current frame. The parameters\n317\tof the global and local models are denoted by θg and θl , respectively.\n318\tUnder this factorization, the large global LLM is evaluated only once per audio frame, while the\n319\tlightweight local LLM completes the remaining seven codebooks along a short, fixed-length depth\n320\taxis. Compared with flattening all eight codebooks into a single temporal token sequence, this design\n321\tsubstantially reduces the sequence length and computational workload of the global model while\n322\tretaining the acoustic capacity provided by multi-codebook representations.\n323\t\n324\tGlobal LLM. The global component is initialized from Qwen3-8B and serves as the temporal\n325\tbackbone of hybird-LM. Structured music annotations and lyrics are serialized as a text prefix, while\n326\tthe embeddings of the eight codebooks from each preceding audio frame are aggregated into a\n327\tsingle frame-level representation. At each temporal step, the global LLM predicts the first codebook\n328\ttoken c0t and produces the hidden state hgt for the local branch. Operating at the frame level allows\n329\tthe model to focus on long-range musical dependencies, including melody development, rhythmic\n330\tcontinuity, lyric progression, section transitions, repetition, and overall song structure. Its extended\n331\tcontext window supports complete-song generation of up to five minutes.\n332\t\n333\tLocal LLM. The local component is a lightweight 0.4B-parameter causal Transformer trained from\n334\tscratch. Conditioned on the global hidden state hgt and the first codebook token c0t , it autoregressively\n335\tpredicts the remaining codebooks c1t through c7t along the codebook axis. Teacher forcing is used\n336\tduring training, while the residual codebooks are generated sequentially during inference. Once all\n337\t\n338\t\n339\t                                                    7\n340\t\feight codebooks of frame t have been generated, their embeddings are aggregated into a frame-level\n341\trepresentation and fed back to the global LLM for prediction of the next frame.\n342\t\n343\tPrompt conditioning and classifier-free guidance. The text prompt consists of two complementary\n344\tcomponents: a music description and structured lyrics. The music description specifies high-level\n345\tattributes such as style, mood, instrumentation, vocal characteristics, usage scenario, and other\n346\tcommon musical properties. The lyrics provide the textual content of the song and retain explicit\n347\tsection markers, such as [Verse], [Chorus], [Bridge], and [Instrumental], to describe the\n348\tintended song structure. Together, these two components provide control over the overall musical\n349\tcharacteristics, lyrical content, and sectional organization of the generated song.\n350\tTo enable classifier-free guidance, the textual condition is randomly removed for 10% of the training\n351\texamples and replaced with a learned unconditional embedding. During inference, the conditional\n352\tand unconditional predictions can be combined to strengthen adherence to the requested musical\n353\tattributes and lyrics without changing the hierarchical decoding procedure.\n354\t\n355\tWeighted training objective. The global and local components are jointly optimized using masked\n356\tnext-token cross-entropy. Let Mk denote the set of valid target positions associated with codebook k.\n357\tThe loss for each codebook is defined as\n358\t                                     1   X\n359\t                                               log p ckt | X, c<t , c<k\n360\t                                                                        \u0001\n361\t                           Lk = −                                    t    .                       (2)\n362\t                                   |Mk |\n363\t                                           t∈Mk\n364\t\n365\t\n366\tBecause the seven residual codebooks represent related acoustic refinements, directly summing their\n367\tlosses would cause the local branch to dominate the total objective merely because it contains more\n368\tprediction targets. We therefore average the residual-codebook losses and assign a larger weight to\n369\tthe first codebook:\n370\t                                                         7\n371\t                                                      1X\n372\t                                    Laudio = 5L0 +          Lk .                                (3)\n373\t                                                      7\n374\t                                                             k=1\n375\t\n376\tThe global c0 objective and the aggregated local objective therefore have a weight ratio of 5:1. This\n377\tweighting reflects the asymmetric roles of the two branches: errors in c0 directly affect temporal\n378\tplanning and propagate to subsequent frames, whereas c1 –c7 primarily refine timbre and local\n379\tacoustic detail. The textual prefix is used solely as conditioning context and is excluded from the\n380\taudio-token prediction loss.\n381\t\n382\t2.4   FullDiT\n383\t\n384\tFullDiT is an 8B-parameter conditional DiT that converts the discrete music plan generated by\n385\thybird-LM into a high-fidelity continuous acoustic representation. As illustrated in Figure 6, it takes\n386\tthe full sequence of 8-codebook RVQ tokens together with the original lyrics and text caption, and\n387\tgenerates an acoustic latent that is subsequently converted into a 48-kHz stereo waveform by a fixed\n388\tVAE decoder. Instead of treating the audio tokens as a deterministic reconstruction target, the model\n389\tperforms conditional acoustic generation from Gaussian noise, allowing it to enrich acoustic details\n390\tand correct locally imperfect token predictions.\n391\t\n392\tHigh-fidelity data for FullDiT. Starting from the 43.8-million-song pre-training pool, we construct\n393\ta separate renderer corpus with stricter acoustic-quality constraints. The selection jointly considers\n394\teffective bandwidth, stereo image width, Audiobox quality estimates, and source bitrate in order\n395\tto reject bandwidth-limited, spatially collapsed, or otherwise degraded audio. Approximately 5.8\n396\tmillion lossless-quality songs are retained for FullDiT training. This dedicated corpus enables the\n397\trenderer to synthesize high-fidelity music in 48-kHz stereo.\n398\t\n399\tFrame-aligned codec conditioning. For each time frame, the eight RVQ tokens are mapped\n400\tthrough codebook-specific embedding tables, fused, and projected to the hidden dimension of the DiT.\n401\tThe resulting codec condition is directly added to the audio state at the corresponding time frame:\n402\t                                                      (0)\n403\t             ecodec\n404\t              i     = Fuse8k=1 Embk (ci,k ),       ai       = EmbedAudio(zt,i ) + ecodec\n405\t                                                                                   i     ,          (4)\n406\t\n407\t\n408\t                                                  8\n409\t\fFigure 6: Architecture of FullDiT. Given full-song RVQ tokens, lyrics, and a text caption, FullDiT\n410\tinjects frame-aligned codec embeddings into the audio hidden states and performs non-causal full-\n411\tsong flow matching to generate a continuous VAE latent.\n412\t\n413\t\n414\twhere ci,k denotes the token from codebook k at frame i, and zt,i denotes the corresponding frame of\n415\tthe noisy VAE latent. This design preserves the temporal correspondence between the discrete music\n416\tplan and the generated acoustic representation.\n417\t\n418\tFull-context text and audio modeling. Lyrics and captions are independently encoded and pro-\n419\tvided directly to FullDiT rather than being used only by hybird-LM. The caption represents global\n420\tattributes such as genre, instrumentation, mood, and production style, while the lyrics provide pho-\n421\tnetic content and section-level structure. In each DiT block, the audio states serve as queries, while\n422\tthe encoded lyrics, caption, and audio states jointly form the key-value context. In addition, the audio\n423\tsequence is modeled with non-causal self-attention over the entire song. The model can process up to\n424\t8192 frames, corresponding to 327.68 seconds at 25 Hz, enabling it to model verse–chorus repetition,\n425\tsection transitions, recurring motifs, and long-range timbral consistency within a single generation\n426\ttrajectory.\n427\t\n428\tFlow-matching objective. Let σ ∈ [0, 1] denote the flow-path coordinate, with σ = 0 correspond-\n429\ting to data and σ = 1 to Gaussian noise. Given a target acoustic latent z0 and ϵ ∼ N (0, I), we\n430\tdefine\n431\t                            zσ = (1 − σ)z0 + σϵ,         vσ∗ = ϵ − z0 .                          (5)\n432\tConditioned on the codec sequence c, lyrics l, and caption p, FullDiT is trained with the following\n433\tflow-matching objective:\n434\t                                h                                         i\n435\t                                                                        2\n436\t                       LFM = E w(σ) ∥vθ (zσ , σ, c, l, p) − (ϵ − z0 )∥2 .                        (6)\n437\t\n438\tDuring inference, the corresponding reverse trajectory is solved from Gaussian noise to the generated\n439\tacoustic latent, which is then decoded into the final waveform.\n440\t\n441\tError-Matched Distractor Conditioning. During training, codec tokens extracted from the target\n442\taudio are perfectly aligned with the target latent, whereas inference-time tokens predicted by hybird-\n443\tLM may contain local errors. To reduce this train–inference mismatch, we introduce Error-Matched\n444\tDistractor Conditioning (EDMC). For each codebook k, a token is replaced with probability pk =\n445\t1 − Acc@1k , where Acc@1k is the teacher-forced top-1 accuracy of the upstream hybird-LM. When\n446\treplacement is applied, a near-miss token is sampled from the cosine top-Kk neighborhood of the\n447\toriginal token in the corresponding codec embedding space. Importantly, EDMC modifies only the\n448\tcodec condition while keeping the original acoustic target z0 unchanged. The model therefore learns\n449\tto selectively correct plausible codec errors using the remaining codec information, text conditions,\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "8c56a85d-92a8-4274-a82c-ece638c779b4", "uuid": "cb8c0ba3-9f13-4f44-8dff-747fe003ff6e", "timestamp": "2026-07-23T07:53:27.696Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_2607_20253.txt", "content": "\n\n\nFigure 3: Three-stage training of the proposed tokenizer, which consists of BEST-RQ-style pretraining,\nmulti-task finetuning, and RVQ token training.\n\nThe proposed tokenizer maps raw music audio into discrete token sequences for downstream language\nmodeling and acoustic generation. As shown in Figure 3, we train it with a three-stage pipeline\nconsisting of BEST-RQ-style pretraining[7], multi-task finetuning, and RVQ token training.\n\nArchitecture. The tokenizer is built on a 24-layer Conformer encoder, followed by an 8-codebook\nresidual vector quantization (RVQ) module. Each codebook has a size of 8192. Given input music\naudio features, the encoder produces continuous latent representations, which are then quantized into\ndiscrete token sequences by the RVQ module. The resulting tokens provide a compact yet expressive\nrepresentation of musical content and serve as the target space for hybird-LM.\n\nStage 1: BEST-RQ-style pretraining. In the first stage, we pretrain the 24-layer Conformer\nencoder with a BEST-RQ-style objective[7]. Masked audio features are encoded and trained to\npredict random-projection-quantized targets, enabling the encoder to learn robust contextual and\nsemantic representations from large-scale music audio.\n\nStage 2: Multi-task finetuning. In the second stage, we finetune the encoder with multiple training\nobjectives, including ASR, reconstruction, and chroma prediction, as shown in Figure 3. This stage\nimproves the representation quality for lyrics, acoustic details, and pitch-related musical structure.\n\nStage 3: RVQ token training. In the final stage, we introduce the RVQ module and train the\ntokenizer to generate discrete tokens. Specifically, we use the bottom 12 layers of the Conformer\nencoder as a frozen feature extractor, while the top 12 layers together with the 8-codebook RVQ\nmodule are optimized for tokenization. This stage yields discrete tokens that preserve semantic\ninformation while maintaining high reconstruction fidelity.\n\n2.3     hybird-LM\n\n2.3.1    Data and Training Pipeline\nThe training of hybird-LM follows a multi-stage pipeline consisting of large-scale pre-training, style-\nbalanced mid-training, and high-quality supervised fine-tuning. We first collect a large-scale song\ncorpus from diverse digital music sources, covering a wide range of languages, musical styles, vocal\ncharacteristics, and production practices. To construct a reliable training corpus, we apply a multi-\nstage curation process that considers metadata completeness together with complementary perceptual\nand musical-quality estimates from SongEval [31], Audiobox Aesthetics [22], and SongBench [26].\nAfter filtering and deduplication, a corpus containing tens of millions of songs is retained for large-\nscale training.\n\nFine-grained music annotation. An overview of the complete data curation and staged training\npipeline is shown in Figure 4. To provide expressive and controllable conditioning signals, we\n\n\n                                                  5\n\f            Figure 4: Overview of the music data curation and staged training pipeline.\n\n\ndesign a fine-grained annotation system that describes each song from multiple complementary\nperspectives. The annotation taxonomy covers musical style and substyle, mood, instrumentation,\nvocal characteristics, segment-level song structure, usage scenario, and common musical attributes\nsuch as tempo, key, rhythmic characteristics, energy, and production-related descriptors. Structural\nannotations identify segments such as intro, verse, pre-chorus, chorus, bridge, instrumental break,\nand outro whenever applicable. These annotations are normalized into a structured representation\nand, together with lyrics and section markers, form the textual condition supplied to hybird-LM.\n\nStage 1: Large-scale pre-training. The full curated corpus is used to establish broad multilingual\nand multi-style coverage. During this stage, the model learns general text-to-music correspondence,\nframe-level audio-token prediction, and long-range musical dependencies. We pre-train hybird-LM\nusing a relatively high learning rate for a limited number of passes over the large-scale corpus.\n\nStage 2: Style-balanced mid-training. Large-scale music corpora naturally exhibit a long-tailed\ndistribution in which a small number of popular styles dominate the training data. We therefore use\nthe SongBench Musicality score to select a higher-quality subset and rebalance it across a broad set of\nmusical style categories, including Pop, Rock, Folk, Hip-Hop, R&B, Soul, and EDM, etc. Together\nwith additional high-quality instrumental music, this process yields a multi-million-song training\ncorpus. We continue training on this corpus using a reduced learning rate. This stage improves both\nmusical quality and style coverage while reducing over-specialization toward dominant genres.\n\nStage 3: Supervised fine-tuning. For the final stage, we select a compact subset of high-quality\nsongs from the curated data pool. The selected examples exhibit strong musicality, reliable annota-\ntions, clear structural organization, and close agreement between the audio and its textual conditions.\nWe perform supervised fine-tuning using a substantially lower learning rate. This final refinement\nstage further improves musical coherence, condition following, generation stability, and overall\nperceptual quality.\n\n2.3.2   Hierarchical Autoregressive Architecture\nAs illustrated in Figure 5, hybird-LM adopts a hierarchical autoregressive architecture that separates\nlong-range temporal modeling from within-frame acoustic modeling. Following the factorization\nintroduced by HeartMuLa [30], the architecture consists of an 8B-parameter global LLM operating\nalong the temporal axis and a lightweight 0.4B-parameter local LLM operating along the RVQ\ncodebook axis.\n\n\n                                                  6\n\fFigure 5: Overview of the hierarchical autoregressive architecture of hybird-LM. Structured music\nannotations and lyrics are provided as textual conditions, with optional frame-aligned melody tokens\nused for cover generation. The 8B global LLM predicts the first codebook token c0t once per audio\nframe and models long-range temporal dependencies, while the 0.4B local LLM autoregressively\npredicts the residual codebook tokens c1t –c7t within the frame.\n\n\nThe model receives structured music annotations and lyrics as textual conditions and predicts discrete\naudio tokens generated by the proposed tokenizer. Let X denote the textual condition, comprising\nthe structured music description and lyrics, and let M = (M MIDI , M F0 ) denote the optional frame-\naligned melody condition used for cover generation. For non-cover generation, M = ∅. Given\nan audio-token sequence A = (c1 , . . . , cT ), each audio frame is represented by eight RVQ tokens,\nct = (c0t , . . . , c7t ). The first codebook c0t provides a compact frame-level representation for global\ntemporal modeling, while c1t –c7t progressively encode residual acoustic information. Each codebook\ncontains 8,192 entries together with an end-of-sequence token, and the tokenizer operates at a frame\nrate of 25 Hz.\nWe factorize the conditional audio-token distribution as\n                                T\n                                   \"                         7\n                                                                                    #\n                               Y                            \u0001Y         g <k\n                                        0                         k\n                                                                                  \u0001\n               p(A | X, M ) =        p ct | c<t , X, M ; θg    p ct | ht , ct ; θl ,                  (1)\n                                 t=1                          k=1\n\nwhere hgt denotes the global hidden state conditioned on X and M , c<t represents all preceding audio\nframes, and c<k\n              t  denotes the codebooks already generated within the current frame. The parameters\nof the global and local models are denoted by θg and θl , respectively.\nUnder this factorization, the large global LLM is evaluated only once per audio frame, while the\nlightweight local LLM completes the remaining seven codebooks along a short, fixed-length depth\naxis. Compared with flattening all eight codebooks into a single temporal token sequence, this design\nsubstantially reduces the sequence length and computational workload of the global model while\nretaining the acoustic capacity provided by multi-codebook representations.\n\nGlobal LLM. The global component is initialized from Qwen3-8B and serves as the temporal\nbackbone of hybird-LM. Structured music annotations and lyrics are serialized as a text prefix, while\nthe embeddings of the eight codebooks from each preceding audio frame are aggregated into a\nsingle frame-level representation. At each temporal step, the global LLM predicts the first codebook\ntoken c0t and produces the hidden state hgt for the local branch. Operating at the frame level allows\nthe model to focus on long-range musical dependencies, including melody development, rhythmic\ncontinuity, lyric progression, section transitions, repetition, and overall song structure. Its extended\ncontext window supports complete-song generation of up to five minutes.\n\nLocal LLM. The local component is a lightweight 0.4B-parameter causal Transformer trained from\nscratch. Conditioned on the global hidden state hgt and the first codebook token c0t , it autoregressively\npredicts the remaining codebooks c1t through c7t along the codebook axis. Teacher forcing is used\nduring training, while the residual codebooks are generated sequentially during inference. Once all\n\n\n                                                    7\n\feight codebooks of frame t have been generated, their embeddings are aggregated into a frame-level\nrepresentation and fed back to the global LLM for prediction of the next frame.\n\nPrompt conditioning and classifier-free guidance. The text prompt consists of two complementary\ncomponents: a music description and structured lyrics. The music description specifies high-level\nattributes such as style, mood, instrumentation, vocal characteristics, usage scenario, and other\ncommon musical properties. The lyrics provide the textual content of the song and retain explicit\nsection markers, such as [Verse], [Chorus], [Bridge], and [Instrumental], to describe the\nintended song structure. Together, these two components provide control over the overall musical\ncharacteristics, lyrical content, and sectional organization of the generated song.\nTo enable classifier-free guidance, the textual condition is randomly removed for 10% of the training\nexamples and replaced with a learned unconditional embedding. During inference, the conditional\nand unconditional predictions can be combined to strengthen adherence to the requested musical\nattributes and lyrics without changing the hierarchical decoding procedure.\n\nWeighted training objective. The global and local components are jointly optimized using masked\nnext-token cross-entropy. Let Mk denote the set of valid target positions associated with codebook k.\nThe loss for each codebook is defined as\n                                     1   X\n                                               log p ckt | X, c<t , c<k\n                                                                        \u0001\n                           Lk = −                                    t    .                       (2)\n                                   |Mk |\n                                           t∈Mk\n\n\nBecause the seven residual codebooks represent related acoustic refinements, directly summing their\nlosses would cause the local branch to dominate the total objective merely because it contains more\nprediction targets. We therefore average the residual-codebook losses and assign a larger weight to\nthe first codebook:\n                                                         7\n                                                      1X\n                                    Laudio = 5L0 +          Lk .                                (3)\n                                                      7\n                                                             k=1\n\nThe global c0 objective and the aggregated local objective therefore have a weight ratio of 5:1. This\nweighting reflects the asymmetric roles of the two branches: errors in c0 directly affect temporal\nplanning and propagate to subsequent frames, whereas c1 –c7 primarily refine timbre and local\nacoustic detail. The textual prefix is used solely as conditioning context and is excluded from the\naudio-token prediction loss.\n\n2.4   FullDiT\n\nFullDiT is an 8B-parameter conditional DiT that converts the discrete music plan generated by\nhybird-LM into a high-fidelity continuous acoustic representation. As illustrated in Figure 6, it takes\nthe full sequence of 8-codebook RVQ tokens together with the original lyrics and text caption, and\ngenerates an acoustic latent that is subsequently converted into a 48-kHz stereo waveform by a fixed\nVAE decoder. Instead of treating the audio tokens as a deterministic reconstruction target, the model\nperforms conditional acoustic generation from Gaussian noise, allowing it to enrich acoustic details\nand correct locally imperfect token predictions.\n\nHigh-fidelity data for FullDiT. Starting from the 43.8-million-song pre-training pool, we construct\na separate renderer corpus with stricter acoustic-quality constraints. The selection jointly considers\neffective bandwidth, stereo image width, Audiobox quality estimates, and source bitrate in order\nto reject bandwidth-limited, spatially collapsed, or otherwise degraded audio. Approximately 5.8\nmillion lossless-quality songs are retained for FullDiT training. This dedicated corpus enables the\nrenderer to synthesize high-fidelity music in 48-kHz stereo.\n\nFrame-aligned codec conditioning. For each time frame, the eight RVQ tokens are mapped\nthrough codebook-specific embedding tables, fused, and projected to the hidden dimension of the DiT.\nThe resulting codec condition is directly added to the audio state at the corresponding time frame:\n                                                      (0)\n             ecodec\n              i     = Fuse8k=1 Embk (ci,k ),       ai       = EmbedAudio(zt,i ) + ecodec\n                                                                                   i     ,          (4)\n\n\n                                                  8\n\fFigure 6: Architecture of FullDiT. Given full-song RVQ tokens, lyrics, and a text caption, FullDiT\ninjects frame-aligned codec embeddings into the audio hidden states and performs non-causal full-\nsong flow matching to generate a continuous VAE latent.\n\n\nwhere ci,k denotes the token from codebook k at frame i, and zt,i denotes the corresponding frame of\nthe noisy VAE latent. This design preserves the temporal correspondence between the discrete music\nplan and the generated acoustic representation.\n\nFull-context text and audio modeling. Lyrics and captions are independently encoded and pro-\nvided directly to FullDiT rather than being used only by hybird-LM. The caption represents global\nattributes such as genre, instrumentation, mood, and production style, while the lyrics provide pho-\nnetic content and section-level structure. In each DiT block, the audio states serve as queries, while\nthe encoded lyrics, caption, and audio states jointly form the key-value context. In addition, the audio\nsequence is modeled with non-causal self-attention over the entire song. The model can process up to\n8192 frames, corresponding to 327.68 seconds at 25 Hz, enabling it to model verse–chorus repetition,\nsection transitions, recurring motifs, and long-range timbral consistency within a single generation\ntrajectory.\n\nFlow-matching objective. Let σ ∈ [0, 1] denote the flow-path coordinate, with σ = 0 correspond-\ning to data and σ = 1 to Gaussian noise. Given a target acoustic latent z0 and ϵ ∼ N (0, I), we\ndefine\n                            zσ = (1 − σ)z0 + σϵ,         vσ∗ = ϵ − z0 .                          (5)\nConditioned on the codec sequence c, lyrics l, and caption p, FullDiT is trained with the following\nflow-matching objective:\n                                h                                         i\n                                                                        2\n                       LFM = E w(σ) ∥vθ (zσ , σ, c, l, p) − (ϵ − z0 )∥2 .                        (6)\n\nDuring inference, the corresponding reverse trajectory is solved from Gaussian noise to the generated\nacoustic latent, which is then decoded into the final waveform.\n\nError-Matched Distractor Conditioning. During training, codec tokens extracted from the target\naudio are perfectly aligned with the target latent, whereas inference-time tokens predicted by hybird-\nLM may contain local errors. To reduce this train–inference mismatch, we introduce Error-Matched\nDistractor Conditioning (EDMC). For each codebook k, a token is replaced with probability pk =\n1 − Acc@1k , where Acc@1k is the teacher-forced top-1 accuracy of the upstream hybird-LM. When\nreplacement is applied, a near-miss token is sampled from the cosine top-Kk neighborhood of the\noriginal token in the corresponding codec embedding space. Importantly, EDMC modifies only the\ncodec condition while keeping the original acoustic target z0 unchanged. The model therefore learns\nto selectively correct plausible codec errors using the remaining codec information, text conditions,", "numLines": 250, "startLine": 200, "totalLines": 965}}}
{"type": "assistant", "message": {"id": "msg_1784793219956", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "tool_use", "id": "chatcmpl-tool-b4ab2964780b9f2d", "name": "Read", "input": {"file_path": "/tmp/paper_2607_20253.txt", "limit": 250, "offset": 450}}], "model": "GLM-5.2-w4a8", "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 0, "output_tokens": 0, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 0, "cache_read_input_tokens": 0}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "8c56a85d-92a8-4274-a82c-ece638c779b4", "uuid": "6c653a41-415b-4e72-b45d-87834426bdba"}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b4ab2964780b9f2d", "type": "tool_result", "content": "450\tfull-song context, and its learned acoustic prior.\n451\t\n452\tFour-way classifier-free guidance. At inference time, we use four-way classifier-free guidance\n453\tto control the contributions of codec, lyrics, and caption independently. Let vu , vk , vkl , and vklc\n454\t\n455\t\n456\t                                                   9\n457\t\fdenote the vector-field predictions from the unconditional, codec-only, codec-plus-lyrics, and fully\n458\tconditioned branches, respectively. The final prediction is\n459\t                         vcfg = vu + scodec (vk − vu )\n460\t                                                                                                    (7)\n461\t                                + slyrics (vkl − vk ) + scaption (vklc − vkl ),\n462\twhere the three guidance scales independently control adherence to the audio-token plan, lyrics, and\n463\tglobal musical description. This decomposition provides flexible control over content fidelity and\n464\tacoustic generation quality without requiring separate models.\n465\t\n466\t2.5   Two-Level Melody Modeling\n467\t\n468\t\n469\t                                                   MIDI\n470\t                                                Transcriptor\n471\t                           Separator   Vocal\n472\t                                                   Pitch\n473\t                                                 Extractor                 Melody Token\n474\t\n475\t\n476\t                        Figure 7: The proposed two-level melody tokenizer.\n477\t\n478\tThe proposed melody module models vocal melody with two levels of melodic features, including\n479\tcoarse-grained note-level features and fine-grained pitch-level features. This design provides explicit\n480\tmelodic guidance for cover song generation, allowing the model to capture both the global contour of\n481\tthe singing melody and local pitch variations.\n482\t\n483\tMelody feature extraction. The architecture of the two-level melody tokenizer is illustrated in\n484\tFigure 7. Given a raw input audio, we first apply a BS-RoFormer separator [19] to extract the vocal\n485\ttrack from the mixture. Based on the separated vocal track, we then extract two complementary\n486\tmelody features. First, a MIDI transcription model is used to estimate vocal note sequences, which\n487\tserve as coarse-grained melodic features. These note-level features describe the overall contour and\n488\tprogression of the singing melody. Second, a pitch extraction model is applied to estimate frame-level\n489\tF0 values, which serve as fine-grained melodic features. Compared with MIDI notes, F0 captures\n490\tmore detailed local pitch variations and expressive singing dynamics.\n491\t\n492\tMelody tokenization. After feature extraction, we convert both note-level and pitch-level rep-\n493\tresentations into frame-aligned discrete token sequences at 25 Hz. For MIDI notes, each note is\n494\trepeated along the temporal axis according to its duration, and the corresponding MIDI pitch ID is\n495\tused as a 128-level discrete token. The MIDI ID of 0 is reserved for non-vocal frames. For F0, we\n496\tfirst transform it into the log-pitch domain so that it is better aligned with the pitch scale of MIDI\n497\tnotes. We then quantize it into a 128-level discrete token sequence at 25 Hz, where the zero value is\n498\tsimilarly reserved for non-vocal frames.\n499\tThe resulting MIDI tokens and F0 tokens are fed into hybird-LM in parallel, forming a two-codebook\n500\tdiscrete melody representation. The coarse-grained MIDI tokens guide the overall vocal melody and\n501\thelp preserve the main melodic contour of the reference song, while the fine-grained F0 tokens model\n502\tlocal pitch details, enabling more accurate vocal realization and lyric-to-pitch alignment.\n503\t\n504\t2.6   Reward-Based Post-Training\n505\t\n506\tAlthough large-scale pre-training enables the model to acquire broad music-generation capabilities,\n507\tthe pre-training corpus inevitably contains samples of varying quality. Such data heterogeneity\n508\tmay lead to unstable generation performance, particularly in terms of musical structure, melodic\n509\tcoherence, rhythmic consistency, harmonic plausibility, and overall audio quality. To further improve\n510\tthe lower bound of generation quality and reduce performance variance across different prompts, we\n511\tintroduce a dedicated post-training stage for hybird-LM consisting of supervised fine-tuning (SFT),\n512\tDirect Preference Optimization (DPO), Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO), and On-Policy\n513\tDistillation (OPD). DPO learns from offline preference pairs, whereas GRPO directly optimizes\n514\trewards on samples generated by the current policy. OPD further complements the sparse sequence-\n515\tlevel reward with dense token-level guidance from a frozen high-quality teacher. The illustration of\n516\t\n517\t\n518\t                                                  10\n519\t\fDPO and GRPO are shown in Figure 8. These post-training procedures primarily focus on improving\n520\tthe musicality of the generated results while preserving the general generation capability acquired\n521\tduring pre-training. Beyond hybird-LM, we additionally apply GRPO-based post-training to FullDiT\n522\tto refine audio fidelity at the waveform level, targeting improved vocal-accompaniment balance and\n523\tstereo spatial rendering while keeping the pre-trained generation diversity intact.\n524\t\n525\t\n526\t\n527\t\n528\t        Figure 8: Overview of the RL-based post-training pipeline, including DPO and GRPO.\n529\t\n530\t2.6.1    Supervised Fine-Tuning\n531\tAs described in Stage 3 of the hybird-LM training pipeline, supervised fine-tuning is performed on\n532\tapproximately 600,000 high-quality songs. We optimize the model on this dataset using the standard\n533\tsupervised generation objective:\n534\t                               LSFT = −E(x,y)∼DSFT [log πθ (y | x)] ,                                  (8)\n535\twhere x denotes the conditioning prompt, y denotes the corresponding high-quality music sample,\n536\tand πθ represents the trainable music generation model. This process shifts the model distribution\n537\ttoward higher-quality musical samples and provides a stable initialization for subsequent preference\n538\toptimization.\n539\t\n540\t2.6.2    Direct Preference Optimization\n541\tTo construct the preference dataset for DPO training, the SFT model is first used to generate multiple\n542\tcandidate songs for each prompt. Given a prompt x, the model independently generates six candidate\n543\tsamples under the same generation configuration. All candidates are evaluated using SongBench,\n544\twhich assigns an automatic score s(yi ) to each generated sample according to its overall musical\n545\tquality. Candidate pairs are then constructed according to the difference between the scores.\n546\tFor two candidates yi and yj , a preference pair is retained only when their score difference exceeds a\n547\tpredefined threshold δ. The higher-scoring candidate is treated as the preferred sample y + , whereas\n548\tthe lower-scoring candidate is treated as the rejected sample y − . The resulting preference dataset is\n549\tdefined as\n550\t                           DDPO = x, y + , y − s(y + ) − s(y − ) > δ .\n551\t                                      \b            \u0001\n552\t                                                                                                    (9)\n553\tThis threshold-based pairing strategy filters out ambiguous comparisons in which two candidates\n554\texhibit similar levels of musical quality. It therefore reduces noise in the automatically constructed\n555\tpreference labels and ensures that the model is trained on sufficiently distinguishable positive and\n556\tnegative examples.\n557\tGiven a preference triplet (x, y + , y − ), DPO encourages the trainable model to assign a higher relative\n558\tlikelihood to the preferred sample than to the rejected sample. The DPO objective is formulated as\n559\t\n560\t                                                         πθ (y | x)\n561\t                                     rθ (x, y) = β log                .                              (10)\n562\t                                                         πref (y | x)\n563\t\n564\t                   LDPO = −E(x,y+ ,y− )∼DDPO log σ rθ (x, y + ) − rθ (x, y − ) .\n565\t                                            \u0002                                 \u0001\u0003\n566\t                                                                                                     (11)\n567\t\n568\t\n569\t                                                   11\n570\t\fwhere rθ (x, y) denotes the implicit reward defined by the log-likelihood ratio between the trainable\n571\tpolicy πθ and the frozen reference policy. The DPO pipeline is illustrated in Figure 8.\n572\tIn addition to the standard DPO objective, we introduce an auxiliary SFT loss computed only on the\n573\tpreferred samples. Thus, the final optimization objective is defined as\n574\t                                    Lpost = LDPO + λSFT L+\n575\t                                                         SFT ,                                    (12)\n576\twhere λSFT controls the contribution of the auxiliary positive-sample SFT objective.\n577\tThe standard DPO loss optimizes the relative preference margin between the preferred and rejected\n578\tgenerations, whereas the auxiliary SFT loss directly increases the likelihood of the preferred samples.\n579\tCombining the two objectives prevents the model from relying exclusively on relative ranking signals\n580\tand provides an explicit learning signal toward high-quality musical outputs. This joint training\n581\tobjective improves optimization stability, preserves the fundamental generation capabilities learned\n582\tduring pre-training and SFT, and encourages the output distribution to move consistently toward\n583\tsamples with stronger musicality.\n584\t\n585\t2.6.3   Group Relative Policy Optimization\n586\tFor each conditioning input x, which consists of a caption, lyrics, and optional melody conditions,\n587\thybird-LM independently samples a group of G candidate music-token sequences {yi }G     i=1 under the\n588\tsame generation configuration. Each candidate is rendered into audio and automatically evaluated by\n589\tSongBench for overall musical quality. SongBench scores melody, arrangement, structure, likability,\n590\tvocal quality, instrumental quality, and mixing, and aggregates these dimensions into a scalar reward\n591\tri .\n592\tFor each group, we compute the normalized relative advantage\n593\t                                                   ri − µG\n594\t                                            Ai =           ,                                      (13)\n595\t                                                   σG + ϵ\n596\twhere µG and σG denote the mean and standard deviation of rewards within the group. To maintain a\n597\treliable and stable reward signal, groups whose reward variance falls below a minimum threshold are\n598\texcluded from the policy-gradient objective.\n599\tLet\n600\t                                              πθ (yi,t | x, yi,<t )\n601\t                                    ρi,t (θ) =                       ,                            (14)\n602\t                                             πold (yi,t | x, yi,<t )\n603\tbe the token-level importance ratio. The clipped GRPO objective is\n604\t             LGRPO = −Ei,t [min (ρi,t Ai , clip (ρi,t , 1 − ϵl , 1 + ϵh ) Ai )] + βLref-KL ,      (15)\n605\twhere the reference-policy KL term constrains excessive deviation from the initialization policy.\n606\tOptimizing solely with the group-relative policy objective can be unstable, especially for long music\n607\tsequences in which thousands of tokens share a single terminal reward. To stabilize training and\n608\tprovide a denser learning signal, we augment GRPO with an auxiliary online rejection-sampling\n609\tfine-tuning (RSFT) objective. For each on-policy group, we select the highest-reward sample as\n610\ta pseudo-label and optimize its music tokens using standard token-level negative log-likelihood,\n611\tdenoted by LRSFT . The resulting GRPO–RSFT objective is\n612\t                             LGRPO-RSFT = LGRPO + λRSFT LRSFT ,                                   (16)\n613\tHere, λRSFT controls the contribution of the auxiliary RSFT objective, while GRPO remains the\n614\tprimary policy-optimization objective.\n615\tOverall, GRPO alignment improves musicality, global structure, and listenability, resulting in more\n616\tcoherent and stable full-song generation.\n617\t\n618\t2.6.4   On-Policy Distillation\n619\tThe GRPO stage improves sequence-level music quality through on-policy exploration, but its\n620\tscalar terminal reward provides limited token-level guidance. Although online RSFT supplies a\n621\tdenser signal, it retains only one sampled sequence per group and converts the reward ranking into\n622\ta one-hot token target. Meanwhile, an SFT teacher trained on curated high-quality data captures\n623\t\n624\t\n625\t                                                   12\n626\t\fa strong prior over high-quality music generation, but is slightly overfitted to this narrower data\n627\tdistribution and consequently exhibits reduced generation diversity. Following GRPO training, we\n628\tintroduce On-Policy Distillation (OPD) while retaining the GRPO objective. The student continues\n629\tto sample trajectories from its current policy, preserving the quality gains from GRPO and the\n630\tstudent’s generation diversity, while the frozen teacher provides soft distributional guidance on the\n631\tsame student-generated prefixes. In this way, OPD transfers the teacher’s high-quality prior without\n632\trequiring direct imitation of teacher-generated trajectories or overly constraining policy exploration.\n633\tThe student first generates trajectories with its current policy. For every valid response-token position,\n634\tthe same sampled prefix is then fed to both the frozen teacher and the trainable student under teacher\n635\t               (T )     (T )\n636\tforcing. Let ptea and pθ denote their temperature-scaled full-vocabulary distributions conditioned\n637\ton the same sampled prefix. The OPD loss is\n638\t                                T2 X           \u0010\n639\t                                                  (T )               (T )\n640\t                                                                                    \u0011\n641\t                    LOPD =               DKL ptea (· | x, y<t ) ∥ pθ (· | x, y<t ) ,                 (17)\n642\t                               |M |\n643\t                                   t∈M\n644\t\n645\twhere M is the set of valid response-token positions and T is the distillation temperature. The\n646\tcombined GRPO–OPD objective is\n647\t                               LGRPO-OPD = LGRPO + λOPD LOPD ,                                       (18)\n648\t\n649\tThe teacher remains fixed throughout distillation. A moderate OPD weight regularizes the student\n650\twithout suppressing exploration, whereas an overly large weight can force rapid convergence toward\n651\tthe teacher and weaken the benefit of online reward optimization. OPD improves generation quality\n652\tand stylistic consistency by transferring the teacher’s high-quality prior, while retaining the diversity\n653\tof the on-policy student distribution.\n654\t\n655\t2.6.5    Post-Training for FullDiT\n656\tWe apply FlowTTS-GRPO [24, 23, 18] to FullDiT for post-training refinement, targeting audio fidelity\n657\tand musical balance. We convert deterministic Ordinary Differential Equation (ODE) sampling into\n658\ta Stochastic Differential Equation (SDE) sampling for on-policy exploration and optimize group-\n659\trelative terminal rewards. The policy model is conditioned on caption, lyrics, and discrete tokens.\n660\tThe reward combines ViSQOL[11, 6] audio quality and an internal music reward model, normalized\n661\tby their per-batch standard deviations:\n662\t\n663\t                                         RViSQOL            RMusic\n664\t                              R = λ1                 + λ2              ,                             (19)\n665\t                                       std(RViSQOL )      std(RMusic )\n666\t\n667\tThis normalization makes λ1 and λ2 express the intended objective balance rather than raw reward\n668\tvariance. This post-training stage further improves vocal-accompaniment balance and stereo spatial\n669\trendering, encouraging the model to produce well-balanced mixes with immersive spatial presentation.\n670\tSDE exploration is restricted to an early-step window, and classifier-free guidance [12] is omitted\n671\tduring rollouts.\n672\t\n673\t3     Results\n674\t3.1     Controlled FullDiT Ablations\n675\t\n676\tTo isolate the contributions of the FullDiT design choices from model scale, we additionally train a\n677\tcomplete 1.5B-parameter FullDiT (M1) specifically for controlled ablation studies. We construct\n678\tthree matched 1.5B variants that remove EDMC (M2), full-song training context (M3a), or decoder-\n679\tside text conditioning (M3b), respectively. All comparisons in this subsection are therefore conducted\n680\tamong the 1.5B models in Table 1; the end-to-end system results reported elsewhere use the 8B\n681\tFullDiT described in Section 2.4.\n682\t\n683\tEvaluation regimes. We evaluate the four models under three complementary codec conditions.\n684\tFor clean GT-codec, a frozen tokenizer extracts ground-truth codec tokens from each held-out song,\n685\twhich FullDiT uses to reconstruct the paired source audio. For synthetic-corrupted GT-codec, we\n686\t\n687\t\n688\t                                                   13\n689\t\fTable 1: Configurations of the controlled 1.5B FullDiT models. Except for the factor identified in the\n690\tfinal column, the ablation models follow the same architecture and supervised-training setup as M1.\n691\tModel            Scale         EDMC            Training audio context     Decoder-side text     Role\n692\tM1               1.5B           on             full song                  caption + lyrics      complete controlled model\n693\tM2               1.5B           off            full song,                 caption + lyrics      EDMC ablation\n694\tM3a              1.5B           on             random local 30 s crop     caption + lyrics      full-context ablation\n695\tM3b              1.5B           on             full song                  learned null_text     decoder-side text ablation\n696\t\n697\t\n698\t\n699\t\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "8c56a85d-92a8-4274-a82c-ece638c779b4", "uuid": "15fca191-0f4e-407f-af01-560fcd3e419c", "timestamp": "2026-07-23T07:53:50.115Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_2607_20253.txt", "content": "full-song context, and its learned acoustic prior.\n\nFour-way classifier-free guidance. At inference time, we use four-way classifier-free guidance\nto control the contributions of codec, lyrics, and caption independently. Let vu , vk , vkl , and vklc\n\n\n                                                   9\n\fdenote the vector-field predictions from the unconditional, codec-only, codec-plus-lyrics, and fully\nconditioned branches, respectively. The final prediction is\n                         vcfg = vu + scodec (vk − vu )\n                                                                                                    (7)\n                                + slyrics (vkl − vk ) + scaption (vklc − vkl ),\nwhere the three guidance scales independently control adherence to the audio-token plan, lyrics, and\nglobal musical description. This decomposition provides flexible control over content fidelity and\nacoustic generation quality without requiring separate models.\n\n2.5   Two-Level Melody Modeling\n\n\n                                                   MIDI\n                                                Transcriptor\n                           Separator   Vocal\n                                                   Pitch\n                                                 Extractor                 Melody Token\n\n\n                        Figure 7: The proposed two-level melody tokenizer.\n\nThe proposed melody module models vocal melody with two levels of melodic features, including\ncoarse-grained note-level features and fine-grained pitch-level features. This design provides explicit\nmelodic guidance for cover song generation, allowing the model to capture both the global contour of\nthe singing melody and local pitch variations.\n\nMelody feature extraction. The architecture of the two-level melody tokenizer is illustrated in\nFigure 7. Given a raw input audio, we first apply a BS-RoFormer separator [19] to extract the vocal\ntrack from the mixture. Based on the separated vocal track, we then extract two complementary\nmelody features. First, a MIDI transcription model is used to estimate vocal note sequences, which\nserve as coarse-grained melodic features. These note-level features describe the overall contour and\nprogression of the singing melody. Second, a pitch extraction model is applied to estimate frame-level\nF0 values, which serve as fine-grained melodic features. Compared with MIDI notes, F0 captures\nmore detailed local pitch variations and expressive singing dynamics.\n\nMelody tokenization. After feature extraction, we convert both note-level and pitch-level rep-\nresentations into frame-aligned discrete token sequences at 25 Hz. For MIDI notes, each note is\nrepeated along the temporal axis according to its duration, and the corresponding MIDI pitch ID is\nused as a 128-level discrete token. The MIDI ID of 0 is reserved for non-vocal frames. For F0, we\nfirst transform it into the log-pitch domain so that it is better aligned with the pitch scale of MIDI\nnotes. We then quantize it into a 128-level discrete token sequence at 25 Hz, where the zero value is\nsimilarly reserved for non-vocal frames.\nThe resulting MIDI tokens and F0 tokens are fed into hybird-LM in parallel, forming a two-codebook\ndiscrete melody representation. The coarse-grained MIDI tokens guide the overall vocal melody and\nhelp preserve the main melodic contour of the reference song, while the fine-grained F0 tokens model\nlocal pitch details, enabling more accurate vocal realization and lyric-to-pitch alignment.\n\n2.6   Reward-Based Post-Training\n\nAlthough large-scale pre-training enables the model to acquire broad music-generation capabilities,\nthe pre-training corpus inevitably contains samples of varying quality. Such data heterogeneity\nmay lead to unstable generation performance, particularly in terms of musical structure, melodic\ncoherence, rhythmic consistency, harmonic plausibility, and overall audio quality. To further improve\nthe lower bound of generation quality and reduce performance variance across different prompts, we\nintroduce a dedicated post-training stage for hybird-LM consisting of supervised fine-tuning (SFT),\nDirect Preference Optimization (DPO), Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO), and On-Policy\nDistillation (OPD). DPO learns from offline preference pairs, whereas GRPO directly optimizes\nrewards on samples generated by the current policy. OPD further complements the sparse sequence-\nlevel reward with dense token-level guidance from a frozen high-quality teacher. The illustration of\n\n\n                                                  10\n\fDPO and GRPO are shown in Figure 8. These post-training procedures primarily focus on improving\nthe musicality of the generated results while preserving the general generation capability acquired\nduring pre-training. Beyond hybird-LM, we additionally apply GRPO-based post-training to FullDiT\nto refine audio fidelity at the waveform level, targeting improved vocal-accompaniment balance and\nstereo spatial rendering while keeping the pre-trained generation diversity intact.\n\n\n\n\n        Figure 8: Overview of the RL-based post-training pipeline, including DPO and GRPO.\n\n2.6.1    Supervised Fine-Tuning\nAs described in Stage 3 of the hybird-LM training pipeline, supervised fine-tuning is performed on\napproximately 600,000 high-quality songs. We optimize the model on this dataset using the standard\nsupervised generation objective:\n                               LSFT = −E(x,y)∼DSFT [log πθ (y | x)] ,                                  (8)\nwhere x denotes the conditioning prompt, y denotes the corresponding high-quality music sample,\nand πθ represents the trainable music generation model. This process shifts the model distribution\ntoward higher-quality musical samples and provides a stable initialization for subsequent preference\noptimization.\n\n2.6.2    Direct Preference Optimization\nTo construct the preference dataset for DPO training, the SFT model is first used to generate multiple\ncandidate songs for each prompt. Given a prompt x, the model independently generates six candidate\nsamples under the same generation configuration. All candidates are evaluated using SongBench,\nwhich assigns an automatic score s(yi ) to each generated sample according to its overall musical\nquality. Candidate pairs are then constructed according to the difference between the scores.\nFor two candidates yi and yj , a preference pair is retained only when their score difference exceeds a\npredefined threshold δ. The higher-scoring candidate is treated as the preferred sample y + , whereas\nthe lower-scoring candidate is treated as the rejected sample y − . The resulting preference dataset is\ndefined as\n                           DDPO = x, y + , y − s(y + ) − s(y − ) > δ .\n                                      \b            \u0001\n                                                                                                    (9)\nThis threshold-based pairing strategy filters out ambiguous comparisons in which two candidates\nexhibit similar levels of musical quality. It therefore reduces noise in the automatically constructed\npreference labels and ensures that the model is trained on sufficiently distinguishable positive and\nnegative examples.\nGiven a preference triplet (x, y + , y − ), DPO encourages the trainable model to assign a higher relative\nlikelihood to the preferred sample than to the rejected sample. The DPO objective is formulated as\n\n                                                         πθ (y | x)\n                                     rθ (x, y) = β log                .                              (10)\n                                                         πref (y | x)\n\n                   LDPO = −E(x,y+ ,y− )∼DDPO log σ rθ (x, y + ) − rθ (x, y − ) .\n                                            \u0002                                 \u0001\u0003\n                                                                                                     (11)\n\n\n                                                   11\n\fwhere rθ (x, y) denotes the implicit reward defined by the log-likelihood ratio between the trainable\npolicy πθ and the frozen reference policy. The DPO pipeline is illustrated in Figure 8.\nIn addition to the standard DPO objective, we introduce an auxiliary SFT loss computed only on the\npreferred samples. Thus, the final optimization objective is defined as\n                                    Lpost = LDPO + λSFT L+\n                                                         SFT ,                                    (12)\nwhere λSFT controls the contribution of the auxiliary positive-sample SFT objective.\nThe standard DPO loss optimizes the relative preference margin between the preferred and rejected\ngenerations, whereas the auxiliary SFT loss directly increases the likelihood of the preferred samples.\nCombining the two objectives prevents the model from relying exclusively on relative ranking signals\nand provides an explicit learning signal toward high-quality musical outputs. This joint training\nobjective improves optimization stability, preserves the fundamental generation capabilities learned\nduring pre-training and SFT, and encourages the output distribution to move consistently toward\nsamples with stronger musicality.\n\n2.6.3   Group Relative Policy Optimization\nFor each conditioning input x, which consists of a caption, lyrics, and optional melody conditions,\nhybird-LM independently samples a group of G candidate music-token sequences {yi }G     i=1 under the\nsame generation configuration. Each candidate is rendered into audio and automatically evaluated by\nSongBench for overall musical quality. SongBench scores melody, arrangement, structure, likability,\nvocal quality, instrumental quality, and mixing, and aggregates these dimensions into a scalar reward\nri .\nFor each group, we compute the normalized relative advantage\n                                                   ri − µG\n                                            Ai =           ,                                      (13)\n                                                   σG + ϵ\nwhere µG and σG denote the mean and standard deviation of rewards within the group. To maintain a\nreliable and stable reward signal, groups whose reward variance falls below a minimum threshold are\nexcluded from the policy-gradient objective.\nLet\n                                              πθ (yi,t | x, yi,<t )\n                                    ρi,t (θ) =                       ,                            (14)\n                                             πold (yi,t | x, yi,<t )\nbe the token-level importance ratio. The clipped GRPO objective is\n             LGRPO = −Ei,t [min (ρi,t Ai , clip (ρi,t , 1 − ϵl , 1 + ϵh ) Ai )] + βLref-KL ,      (15)\nwhere the reference-policy KL term constrains excessive deviation from the initialization policy.\nOptimizing solely with the group-relative policy objective can be unstable, especially for long music\nsequences in which thousands of tokens share a single terminal reward. To stabilize training and\nprovide a denser learning signal, we augment GRPO with an auxiliary online rejection-sampling\nfine-tuning (RSFT) objective. For each on-policy group, we select the highest-reward sample as\na pseudo-label and optimize its music tokens using standard token-level negative log-likelihood,\ndenoted by LRSFT . The resulting GRPO–RSFT objective is\n                             LGRPO-RSFT = LGRPO + λRSFT LRSFT ,                                   (16)\nHere, λRSFT controls the contribution of the auxiliary RSFT objective, while GRPO remains the\nprimary policy-optimization objective.\nOverall, GRPO alignment improves musicality, global structure, and listenability, resulting in more\ncoherent and stable full-song generation.\n\n2.6.4   On-Policy Distillation\nThe GRPO stage improves sequence-level music quality through on-policy exploration, but its\nscalar terminal reward provides limited token-level guidance. Although online RSFT supplies a\ndenser signal, it retains only one sampled sequence per group and converts the reward ranking into\na one-hot token target. Meanwhile, an SFT teacher trained on curated high-quality data captures\n\n\n                                                   12\n\fa strong prior over high-quality music generation, but is slightly overfitted to this narrower data\ndistribution and consequently exhibits reduced generation diversity. Following GRPO training, we\nintroduce On-Policy Distillation (OPD) while retaining the GRPO objective. The student continues\nto sample trajectories from its current policy, preserving the quality gains from GRPO and the\nstudent’s generation diversity, while the frozen teacher provides soft distributional guidance on the\nsame student-generated prefixes. In this way, OPD transfers the teacher’s high-quality prior without\nrequiring direct imitation of teacher-generated trajectories or overly constraining policy exploration.\nThe student first generates trajectories with its current policy. For every valid response-token position,\nthe same sampled prefix is then fed to both the frozen teacher and the trainable student under teacher\n               (T )     (T )\nforcing. Let ptea and pθ denote their temperature-scaled full-vocabulary distributions conditioned\non the same sampled prefix. The OPD loss is\n                                T2 X           \u0010\n                                                  (T )               (T )\n                                                                                    \u0011\n                    LOPD =               DKL ptea (· | x, y<t ) ∥ pθ (· | x, y<t ) ,                 (17)\n                               |M |\n                                   t∈M\n\nwhere M is the set of valid response-token positions and T is the distillation temperature. The\ncombined GRPO–OPD objective is\n                               LGRPO-OPD = LGRPO + λOPD LOPD ,                                       (18)\n\nThe teacher remains fixed throughout distillation. A moderate OPD weight regularizes the student\nwithout suppressing exploration, whereas an overly large weight can force rapid convergence toward\nthe teacher and weaken the benefit of online reward optimization. OPD improves generation quality\nand stylistic consistency by transferring the teacher’s high-quality prior, while retaining the diversity\nof the on-policy student distribution.\n\n2.6.5    Post-Training for FullDiT\nWe apply FlowTTS-GRPO [24, 23, 18] to FullDiT for post-training refinement, targeting audio fidelity\nand musical balance. We convert deterministic Ordinary Differential Equation (ODE) sampling into\na Stochastic Differential Equation (SDE) sampling for on-policy exploration and optimize group-\nrelative terminal rewards. The policy model is conditioned on caption, lyrics, and discrete tokens.\nThe reward combines ViSQOL[11, 6] audio quality and an internal music reward model, normalized\nby their per-batch standard deviations:\n\n                                         RViSQOL            RMusic\n                              R = λ1                 + λ2              ,                             (19)\n                                       std(RViSQOL )      std(RMusic )\n\nThis normalization makes λ1 and λ2 express the intended objective balance rather than raw reward\nvariance. This post-training stage further improves vocal-accompaniment balance and stereo spatial\nrendering, encouraging the model to produce well-balanced mixes with immersive spatial presentation.\nSDE exploration is restricted to an early-step window, and classifier-free guidance [12] is omitted\nduring rollouts.\n\n3     Results\n3.1     Controlled FullDiT Ablations\n\nTo isolate the contributions of the FullDiT design choices from model scale, we additionally train a\ncomplete 1.5B-parameter FullDiT (M1) specifically for controlled ablation studies. We construct\nthree matched 1.5B variants that remove EDMC (M2), full-song training context (M3a), or decoder-\nside text conditioning (M3b), respectively. All comparisons in this subsection are therefore conducted\namong the 1.5B models in Table 1; the end-to-end system results reported elsewhere use the 8B\nFullDiT described in Section 2.4.\n\nEvaluation regimes. We evaluate the four models under three complementary codec conditions.\nFor clean GT-codec, a frozen tokenizer extracts ground-truth codec tokens from each held-out song,\nwhich FullDiT uses to reconstruct the paired source audio. For synthetic-corrupted GT-codec, we\n\n\n                                                   13\n\fTable 1: Configurations of the controlled 1.5B FullDiT models. Except for the factor identified in the\nfinal column, the ablation models follow the same architecture and supervised-training setup as M1.\nModel            Scale         EDMC            Training audio context     Decoder-side text     Role\nM1               1.5B           on             full song                  caption + lyrics      complete controlled model\nM2               1.5B           off            full song,                 caption + lyrics      EDMC ablation\nM3a              1.5B           on             random local 30 s crop     caption + lyrics      full-context ablation\nM3b              1.5B           on             full song                  learned null_text     decoder-side text ablation\n\n\n\n", "numLines": 250, "startLine": 450, "totalLines": 965}}}
