{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-867418592c71e567", "type": "tool_result", "content": "700\tTable 2: Controlled FullDiT ablation results. Upward and downward arrows indicate whether higher\n701\tor lower values are better. Boldface marks the best objective result in each row. Song-level preference\n702\treports the win rate of each ablated model against M1 over non-tied songs.\n703\tEvaluation regime                     Metric                             M1              M2        M3a              M3b\n704\tclean GT-codec                        ViSQOL ↑                          3.3388         3.4578     2.8863           3.3021\n705\t                                      log-mel L1 ↓                      1.1363         0.9248     1.5381           1.1865\n706\t                                      MR-STFT distance ↓                1.7806         1.7896     1.8707           1.8253\n707\tsynthetic-corrupted GT-codec          ViSQOL ↑                          3.2036         2.4342     2.6868           3.1838\n708\t                                      log-mel L1 ↓                      1.1842         2.2372     2.0034           1.2069\n709\t                                      MR-STFT distance ↓                1.7943         2.3346     2.0190           1.8327\n710\tLM-generated codec                    Audiobox PQ ↑                     8.213          8.122      6.011            8.135\n711\t                                      song-level preference vs. M1 ↑     Ref.          30.3%      0.0%             0.0%\n712\t\n713\t\n714\t\n715\t\n716\tapply the same fixed EDMC-targeted corruption to these ground-truth tokens, using codebook-wise\n717\treplacement rates and cosine-KNN near-miss replacements while retaining the original song as\n718\tthe acoustic target. This setting isolates robustness to controlled codec-interface errors. For LM-\n719\tgenerated codec, the frozen upstream hybird-LM predicts codec sequences from the caption and\n720\tlyrics. Since such sequences admit multiple valid acoustic realizations, this regime has no unique\n721\treference waveform. We fix the prompts, lyrics, LM-generated tokens, song lengths, random seeds,\n722\tand sampling recipe across M1–M3b.\n723\t\n724\t\n725\t\n726\tMetrics and sample sizes. All objective results use N = 200 samples: clean and synthetic-\n727\tcorrupted GT-codec share the same 200 held-out songs, while LM-generated codec uses a fixed set\n728\tof 200 generations. For the two GT-codec regimes, ViSQOL [6] measures full-reference perceptual\n729\tsimilarity, with higher values indicating closer perceptual agreement with the source. Log-mel L1 is\n730\tthe mean absolute difference between the generated and reference log-mel spectrograms and measures\n731\tspectral-envelope mismatch, while multi-resolution STFT distance [28] compares magnitude spectra\n732\tat multiple time–frequency resolutions; lower values are better for both distances. For LM-generated\n733\tcodec, we use Audiobox Aesthetics Production Quality (PQ) [22], a learned no-reference estimate of\n734\ttechnical production quality, for which higher is better. We additionally conduct blinded pairwise\n735\tlistening tests on a fixed set of N = 100 songs with five expert raters with musical backgrounds. M1\n736\tserves as the common reference in comparisons with M2, M3a, and M3b, and the reported song-level\n737\tpreference is wins/(wins + losses) after excluding ties. All four models use the same inference\n738\trecipe, including the selected four-way CFG setting (scodec , slyrics , scaption ) = (1, 2, 1).\n739\tTable 2 reveals three consistent trends. First, removing EDMC improves two clean-codec reconstruc-\n740\ttion metrics but substantially degrades all metrics under synthetic corruption; M1 also obtains higher\n741\tPQ and is preferred to M2 under LM-generated codec conditions. This trade-off indicates that EDMC\n742\timproves robustness to imperfect codec inputs rather than merely optimizing clean reconstruction.\n743\tSecond, M3a, which replaces full-song training with random 30-second crops, incurs the largest PQ\n744\tdrop and is consistently worse than M1, highlighting the importance of full-song context for acoustic\n745\trendering. Finally, removing decoder-side caption and lyrics produces smaller objective degradations,\n746\tbut M3b remains consistently below M1 and receives no wins in the non-tied song-level comparison,\n747\tshowing that text provides useful information beyond the codec sequence.\n748\t\n749\t\n750\t                                                                 14\n751\t\f3.2   Fine-grained Automatic Evaluation\n752\t\n753\tTo evaluate the effectiveness of the proposed system, we report complementary automatic evaluations\n754\tusing SongBench [26], SongEval [31], AudioBox-Aesthetic [22], and CMI-Reward [20]. The\n755\tindependent preference-based evaluation is presented in the Introduction.\n756\t\n757\tTable 3: Automatic evaluation results for multilingual vocal music generation on a test set containing\n758\t500 examples, balanced across eight major genres and five languages (Chinese, English, Japanese,\n759\tKorean, and Spanish). We report mean scores from SongBench, SongEval, AudioBox-Aesthetic,\n760\tand CMI-Reward. Higher scores indicate better evaluator outputs except for AudioBox Production\n761\tComplexity, which is a descriptive measure and is not inherently better when larger. The highest\n762\tpoint estimate in each row is shown in bold.\n763\t      Metrics                 Ours     Suno V5.5     Suno V5       Mureka V8     Lyria 3 Pro   MiniMax Music 2.6\n764\t                                                      SongBench\n765\t      Melody                  7.2001    6.6939         6.9202           7.0660     7.0377           6.7245\n766\t      Arrangement             7.3879    6.8406         7.0805           7.2601     7.1511           6.8167\n767\t      Musicality              6.3678    5.8297         6.0096           6.2559     6.1810           5.8823\n768\t      Vocal                   7.6234    7.0981         7.3160           7.6248     7.4560           7.2513\n769\t      Instrumental            7.3517    7.0080         7.1487           7.2585     7.0583           6.8458\n770\t      Mixing                  7.3047    7.0332         7.1101           7.1433     7.0093           6.7397\n771\t      Structure               6.9650    6.6158         6.7363           7.0237     7.0565           6.5637\n772\t                                                       SongEval\n773\t      Coherence               4.5094    4.2905         4.3278           4.3870     4.4673           4.2772\n774\t      Musicality              4.4098    4.1547         4.1970           4.2875     4.3466           4.1781\n775\t      Memorability            4.4663    4.2123         4.2473           4.3680     4.4153           4.2180\n776\t      Clarity                 4.3838    4.1246         4.1741           4.2431     4.3099           4.1448\n777\t      Naturalness             4.2600    4.0046         4.0679           4.1767     4.2021           3.9919\n778\t                                                   AudioBox-Aesthetic\n779\t      Content Enjoyment       7.7089    7.5289         7.5507           7.5921     7.6950           7.6844\n780\t      Content Usefulness      7.9989    7.9535         7.8020           7.8634     7.8919           7.9578\n781\t      Production Complexity   6.8774    6.6486         6.8118           6.8768     6.7561           6.7514\n782\t      Production Quality      8.2986    8.2083         8.1411           8.1098     8.2780           8.2923\n783\t                                                      CMI-Reward\n784\t      Alignment               2.1786    1.9216         1.9119           2.3089     2.0377           2.1546\n785\t      Quality                 2.7611    2.3665         2.3756           2.7590     2.5280           2.6661\n786\t\n787\t\n788\t\n789\tTable 3 compares our system with five representative commercial music generation systems on\n790\tthe same 500 test cases, balanced across eight major genres and five languages: Chinese, English,\n791\tJapanese, Korean, and Spanish. Across the four evaluator families, our system achieves the highest\n792\tmean score in 15 of 18 reported dimensions: five of seven SongBench dimensions, all five SongEval\n793\tdimensions, all four AudioBox-Aesthetic dimensions, and CMI-Reward Quality.\n794\tOn SongBench, our system leads in Melody, Arrangement, Musicality, Instrumental, and Mixing. The\n795\tcorresponding point estimates suggest richer and more memorable melodic lines, stronger harmonic\n796\tand instrumental orchestration, greater overall artistic appeal, more realistic instrument rendering,\n797\tand better track balance and spatial imaging. Its Vocal score (7.6234) nearly matches the best result\n798\tfrom Mureka V8 (7.6248), while the remaining gap on Structure highlights room for improving\n799\tsection organization and transitions.\n800\tOur system obtains the highest mean score in every SongEval dimension. Coherence and Clarity\n801\treflect continuity across song sections and clearly organized musical form; Memorability captures\n802\tdistinctive melodies, rhythmic motifs, and lyrical hooks; Naturalness specifically evaluates vocal\n803\tbreathing and phrasing; and Musicality summarizes melody, harmony, instrumentation, and vocal–\n804\taccompaniment integration. This consistent profile accords with the intended long-range modeling\n805\tobjective of hybird-LM and the perceptual goals of preference alignment. On AudioBox-Aesthetic,\n806\tour system also leads in Content Enjoyment, Content Usefulness, and Production Quality, while\n807\texhibiting the highest Production Complexity. These outputs respectively indicate predicted listening\n808\tappeal, utility as creative source material, technical production quality, and richer component layering;\n809\tProduction Complexity is descriptive rather than a direct measure of quality. Finally, our system\n810\tattains the highest CMI-Reward Quality score, whereas Alignment remains below Mureka V8.\n811\tOverall, the results suggest a balanced advantage in composition, vocal and instrumental realization,\n812\t\n813\t\n814\t                                                          15\n815\t\fmixing, and final rendering, while identifying condition following and explicit structural planning as\n816\tdirections for further improvement.\n817\t\n818\t4   Conclusion\n819\tIn this report, we introduced a unified framework for controllable full-song generation. The pro-\n820\tposed system supports Lyrics-to-Song Generation, Instrumental Music Generation, and Cover Song\n821\tGeneration within a single framework. To address the complexity of music representation, it adopts\n822\ta semantic-aware 8-codebook RVQ tokenizer and hybird-LM for discrete token generation. For\n823\tmelody-guided cover generation, the system further incorporates a two-level melody representation to\n824\tcapture both the main melodic contour and fine-grained pitch variation. To achieve high-fidelity syn-\n825\tthesis for complete songs, FullDiT performs full-song flow matching with non-causal self-attention\n826\tover a continuous VAE latent, using the full-length codec sequence, text caption, and lyrics when\n827\tavailable as conditions. We further investigate DPO, GRPO, and OPD for reward-based hybird-LM\n828\tpost-training and flow-based GRPO for FullDiT refinement. The proposed system demonstrates\n829\tcompetitive performance on the multilingual automatic benchmark and the external Artificial Analysis\n830\tMusic with Vocals leaderboard evaluated in this report. Overall, our framework bridges discrete music\n831\tcomposition, melody control, and full-length high-fidelity synthesis, offering a practical solution for\n832\thigh-quality song generation.\n833\t\n834\tAcknowledgements\n835\tWe thank Hongzhi Cai, Jiayan Cui, Gang Qiao, Biao Tian, Zhicheng Tian, Haixin Wang, Cheng Wen,\n836\tBajian Xiang, Jixing Yu, Peiyun Zeng, Sitong Zhao, Tianyu Zhao, Qixi Zheng and Xin Zhou for their\n837\tvaluable contributions to data curation, system development, evaluation, and infrastructure support.\n838\tNames are listed alphabetically by family name.\n839\t\n840\tReferences\n841\t [1] Andrea Agostinelli, Timo I Denk, Zalán Borsos, Jesse Engel, Mauro Verzetti, Antoine Caillon,\n842\t     Qingqing Huang, Aren Jansen, Adam Roberts, Marco Tagliasacchi, et al. Musiclm: Generating\n843\t     music from text. arXiv preprint arXiv:2301.11325, 2023.\n844\t [2] Artificial Analysis. Music generation benchmarking methodology.      https://\n845\t     artificialanalysis.ai/music/methodology, 2026. Accessed: 2026-07-19.\n846\t [3] Artificial Analysis. Vocals music leaderboard. https://artificialanalysis.ai/music/\n847\t     leaderboard/vocals, 2026. Leaderboard snapshot accessed: 2026-07-18.\n848\t [4] Sungkyun Chang, Emmanouil Benetos, Holger Kirchhoff, and Simon Dixon. Yourmt3+: Multi-\n849\t     instrument music transcription with enhanced transformer architectures and cross-dataset stem\n850\t     augmentation. In 2024 IEEE 34th International Workshop on Machine Learning for Signal\n851\t     Processing (MLSP), pages 1–6. IEEE, 2024.\n852\t [5] Ke Chen, Yusong Wu, Haohe Liu, Marianna Nezhurina, Taylor Berg-Kirkpatrick, and Shlomo\n853\t     Dubnov. Musicldm: Enhancing novelty in text-to-music generation using beat-synchronous\n854\t     mixup strategies. In ICASSP 2024-2024 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech\n855\t     and Signal Processing (ICASSP), pages 1206–1210. IEEE, 2024.\n856\t [6] Michael Chinen, Felicia SC Lim, Jan Skoglund, Nikita Gureev, Feargus O’Gorman, and Andrew\n857\t     Hines. Visqol v3: An open source production ready objective speech and audio metric. In\n858\t     2020 twelfth international conference on quality of multimedia experience